  "opinion": "As a working electrician in Milan who spends just a few times a week on social media, I’ve found that dealing with fake content doesn’t require complex strategies—it’s about practical, everyday habits. My background in hands-on work taught me to verify things before acting, so when I see a post claiming a miracle cure or a viral trend that seems too good to be true, I pause and ask myself: 'Would this hold up in a real-world test?' Like when I once saw a video of someone fixing a car engine with just a hammer and a wrench—something I know takes precision and tools I’ve spent years mastering. I’ve learned to cross-check with trusted sources, like local news or my own experience, rather than jumping to conclusions. My high agreeableness means I avoid spreading rumors, and my moderate neuroticism helps me stay calm when things get confusing. I don’t have a college degree, but I’ve built a reliable way to filter information by focusing on what’s practical and what’s consistent with reality. For instance, if a post says 'This trick will save you money on your electric bill,' I check if it aligns with what I know about energy use from my job. Social media can be noisy, but by keeping it simple—like double-checking facts with real-life experience—I’ve stayed grounded. It’s not about being tech-savvy; it’s about being thoughtful, which is something I’ve learned from my parents, especially my dad who always taught me to 'think before you act.'",
